<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="1312" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1312">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/69</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé d’Affaires’ in France</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_BRW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bliss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Paris</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-04">
                                <hi rend="italic">December 4, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>345. Your 275, 17th. Foreign Office apparently unwilling to give definite
                            answer at this time but states that it does not anticipate any trouble
                            will be encountered from French authorities or representatives by
                            American committee in sending supplies to destitute Belgians in
                            Belgium.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BRW1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bliss</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>